Macedonians vote in referendum on the change of country name
The Macedonians voted on Sunday to decide on the change of the country's name to "the Republic of Macedonia of the North", an initiative that would resolve a dispute for decades with Greece that blocked its applications for membership of the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which forms part of a province called Macedonia, insists that its neighbour's name north represents a complaint about its territory and has banned its entry into NATO and the EU.
The two governments signed an agreement in June based on the proposal for a new name, but the nationalist opponents argued that the change would be a blow to the ethnic identity of the Macedonian population, mostly Slavic.
President Gjorge Ivanov said that he would not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign raised doubts as to whether the voter turnout would be sufficient to meet the 50% required for the referendum to be valid.
The referendum asked: "Is it in favour of entry into NATO and the EU with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?"
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying to continue admission efforts in bodies with the EU and NATO to Macedonia, one of the countries that emerged from the collapse of Yugoslavia.
"I came today to vote for the future of our country, for the young people of Macedonia, so that they can live free under the auspices of the European Union, because that means a safer life for all of us," said Dr. Olivera Georgijska, 79, in Skopje.
Although the referendum is not legally binding, a sufficient number of Members of Parliament said that it would respect the result of the vote to make it decisive.
The change of name would require a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The national election committee stated that there were no irregular records until one afternoon.
However, the influx was only 16%, compared to the 34% obtained in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66% of registered voters came to vote.
"I have come to vote for my children; our place is in Europe," said 62-year-old Gjose Tanevski, a capital elector, Skopje.
The Prime Minister of Macedonia, Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko vote in the referendum on the change of the country's name, which would open the doors for his accession to NATO and the European Union, in Strumica, Macedonia, on 30 September 2018.
In front of the parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small stage and placed chairs in front of the tents mounted by those who would boycott the referendum.
"We are for NATO and for the EU, but we want to stick up and not for the service door," said Kavarkov.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If you don't want to welcome us as Macedonia, we can turn to others like China and Russia to become part of Eurasian integration."
Prime Minister Zaev said that entry into NATO will bring much-needed investments to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20%.
"I believe that the overwhelming majority will be in favour, because more than 80% of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," Zaev said after voting.
According to him, a "yes" would be the "confirmation of our future."
A survey published last Monday by the Institute of Political Research of Macedonia revealed that between 30 and 43% of voters would participate in the referendum, a value lower than the required influx.
Another survey, conducted by Telma TV from Macedonia, revealed that 57% of the respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
Of these, 70% said they would vote yes.
For the success of the referendum, the influx must be more than 50% plus one vote.
The failure of the referendum would represent the first major gap in pro-Western government policy since it took possession of it in May of last year.
