The notification for the Nottingham East working meeting in the sixth quarter mentioned that "we intend that meetings be inclusive and productive".
For the most part of my eight years as a local labour representative in parliament, the meetings of the General Committee were exactly that.
Unfortunately, today, it is no longer the tone of many of the meetings and the promise of "more kind and kind" politics has been long forgotten, if ever it has been realized.
It has become increasingly apparent that the different views are not tolerated in the Labour Party, and that each opinion is judged on whether or not it is acceptable by the leadership of the Party.
This began shortly after Jeremy took the lead, because colleagues with whom he thought he shared a similar political perspective began to expect me to take a turn and assume positions with which he would never agree - whether they were on national security or on the single EU market.
Whenever I speak in public (and it doesn't really matter what I say), there is a stream of insults on social networks that call for "depose", denouncing the policies of the centre, telling me that I must not belong to the Labour Party.
And I'm not the only one going through this.
In fact, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, since the comments I have been given tend to be political.
I am amazed at the professionalism and determination of these colleagues who face a bar of sexist or racist insults every day, but who never go back to them.
One of the most disillusioned aspects of politics in this era is how these levels of insult have become normalized.
Jeremy Corbyn said last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we have ceased to be inclusive, and with each motion of "censing" or amendment of the rules of selection the party narrows its views.
I have received numerous advice over the past two years, urging me to keep my head low, not to be so expressive, and that this would "make everything right" for me.
But that's not why I came to make politics.
Since I joined the Labour Party for 32 years as a student, prompted by the neglect of the Thatcher government that left the classroom of my school literally comprehensive in rubble, I have sought to fight for better public services for those who most need it, either as an author or as a minister in government.
I've never hidden my policies, including in the last elections.
No one in Nottingham East could have become somewhat confused about my political positions and areas of disagreement with the current leadership.
For those who promoted the motion on Friday, all I have to say is that when the country goes to a Brexit that will harm families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on the subject of my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But indeed, the message I have is not for the Momentum of Nottingham; it is for my constituents, members of the Labour Party or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that no threats of "destination" or political files will prevent me from acting in the sense of what I believe to be the interests of all of you.
